  <!-- Section: Common Mistakes -->
  <section id="mistakes" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Underestimating Processing Times</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Current BIIP processing times are 12-24 months—sometimes longer. Don't make business or investment plans that depend on quick visa approval. The Australian system has significant backlogs. Plan for delays and have contingency arrangements.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Choosing the Wrong State for Nomination</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Each state has different priorities and thresholds. NSW and Victoria are competitive with higher requirements; South Australia and Tasmania are more accessible but may have regional requirements. Research state criteria thoroughly and choose strategically—your nomination commits you to that state for initial residence.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Insufficient Documentation of Funds Source</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Australia's anti-money-laundering requirements are strict. You must document the legitimate source of all investment funds—business profits, asset sales, inheritance, etc. Bank statements alone aren't enough. Prepare comprehensive evidence trail going back years. Unexplained wealth will result in visa refusal.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Neglecting 888 Pathway Requirements</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">The 188 visa is provisional—you need to meet ongoing requirements to qualify for 888 permanent residence. 188A holders must demonstrate business ownership and turnover; 188C holders must maintain investment and meet residence days. Start tracking compliance from day one. Keep detailed records—you'll need them for 888 application.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Letting Health Insurance Lapse</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">188 visa holders must maintain health insurance throughout the provisional period. If your coverage lapses, you're in breach of visa conditions. Set up automatic renewals and calendar reminders. A lapsed policy can create complications for your 888 application and potentially affect your visa status.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Healthcare in Australia -->
  <section id="healthcare" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Healthcare in Australia</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Australia has a world-class healthcare system combining public (Medicare) and private options. However, as a 188 provisional visa holder, you don't qualify for Medicare—private insurance is your only option until permanent residence.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Healthcare Access for BIIP Visa Holders</h3>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-6">
      <div class="border border-amber-200 bg-amber-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-3">188 Provisional Visa (No Medicare)</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-amber-800">
          <li>- No Medicare access—private insurance required</li>
          <li>- Must pay full fees at public hospitals if uninsured</li>
          <li>- Private hospitals accessible with appropriate cover</li>
          <li>- Emergency care provided regardless of status</li>
          <li>- Pharmaceutical Benefits Scheme not available</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-green-200 bg-green-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-green-900 mb-3">888 Permanent Visa (Medicare Eligible)</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-green-800">
          <li>Full Medicare eligibility</li>
          <li>Bulk-billed GP and specialist visits</li>
          <li>Free public hospital treatment</li>
          <li>Pharmaceutical Benefits Scheme access</li>
          <li>Many keep private cover for extras/choice</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Private Healthcare in Major Cities</h3>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Australian private healthcare is excellent, particularly in major cities where most BIIP visa holders settle:
    </p>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-6">
      <div class="border border-blue-200 bg-blue-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-blue-900 mb-3">Sydney / Melbourne</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-blue-800">
          <li>- World-class private hospitals</li>
          <li>- Extensive specialist networks</li>
          <li>- International patient services common</li>
          <li>- Short waiting times with private cover</li>
          <li>- Premium pricing—budget accordingly</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-green-200 bg-green-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-green-900 mb-3">Brisbane / Perth / Adelaide</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-green-800">
          <li>- Strong private hospital networks</li>
          <li>- Good specialist availability</li>
          <li>- Slightly lower costs than Sydney/Melbourne</li>
          <li>- Excellent quality of care</li>
          <li>- May need Sydney/Melbourne for rare specialists</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Costs Without Insurance</h3>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Australian healthcare is expensive without coverage:
    </p>

    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 mb-6">
      <li><strong>Private hospital per day:</strong> AUD 1,000-2,500+</li>
      <li><strong>ICU per day:</strong> AUD 3,000-5,000+</li>
      <li><strong>Specialist consultation:</strong> AUD 200-500</li>
      <li><strong>Emergency department:</strong> AUD 500-1,500+</li>
      <li><strong>Surgery:</strong> AUD 5,000-50,000+ depending on procedure</li>
      <li><strong>Childbirth (private):</strong> AUD 10,000-25,000</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-4">
      <p class="text-blue-800">
        <strong>Lifetime Health Cover loading:</strong> Australian private health insurance has a penalty for late starters. If you're over 31 and haven't had Australian cover, you'll pay 2% extra premium per year above 30. This affects Australian policies but not international insurers like Cigna or Bupa Global. Consider this when choosing between Australian and international coverage.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How long must I stay in Australia with a 188C Significant Investor Visa?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          The 188C requires a minimum of 40 days per year in Australia (average over 4 years). This is the most flexible residence requirement among BIIP streams—you can maintain business elsewhere while meeting the minimum. For permanent residence (888), you must accumulate at least 160 days over 4 years, though spending more time demonstrates commitment.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I include my family in the BIIP visa application?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes. Your spouse/partner and dependent children can be included in your initial application or added later. Each family member incurs additional visa fees and must meet health and character requirements. They receive the same visa status and pathway to permanent residence. All family members need health insurance during the provisional period.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What happens to my investment if my visa is refused?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          If your 188 visa is refused, you can withdraw your designated or complying investment—it remains your asset. For 188C, the AUD 5M investment is only made after visa approval, so refusal before investment doesn't affect your capital. Always work with registered migration agents to maximize approval chances.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I work in Australia with a BIIP visa?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          188A and 188E holders must operate their business in Australia—that's the visa purpose. 188B and 188C holders have work rights but are primarily investors, not employees. You can manage your investments and run businesses, but the visa intent is investment/business activity, not general employment. Spouses have full work rights.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How long until I can apply for Australian citizenship?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          After receiving your 888 permanent visa, you must wait 4 years (including at least 1 year as permanent resident) before citizenship eligibility. Total timeline: 188 provisional (4+ years) + 888 requirement + 4 years before citizenship = approximately 9-10 years from initial 188 visa to citizenship eligibility. You must also pass English and civics tests.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What are the risks of the 188C complying investment?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          The AUD 5M complying investment carries investment risk—venture capital allocation (10%) can lose value, and market funds fluctuate. However, you're not required to maintain exactly AUD 5M—the investment can decrease in value without affecting your visa. You cannot withdraw funds early or switch to prohibited investments (like residential property). Work with approved fund managers who understand SIV requirements.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Final Verdict -->
  <section id="verdict" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Final Verdict</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Australia's BIIP program offers genuine pathways to permanent residence for serious business operators and investors. The AUD 5M Significant Investor Visa (188C) stands out for high-net-worth individuals: no points test, no English requirement, and minimal residence obligation make it Australia's most accessible investor route despite the significant capital requirement.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-4">
      For business owners with lower capital but strong operational track records, the 188A Business Innovation stream provides a more affordable entry point—though points requirements and business establishment obligations are substantial. The 188E Entrepreneur stream suits founders with innovative ideas and approved venture funding.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-6">
      The main challenges are processing times (12-24 months) and the provisional-to-permanent pathway (4+ years before 888 eligibility). Private health insurance is mandatory throughout—budget AUD 4,000-10,000 annually depending on coverage level and family size. For investors comfortable with these timelines and ongoing requirements, Australia offers exceptional quality of life, political stability, and a pathway to citizenship in one of the world's most desirable countries.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary-900 mb-3">Bottom Line</h3>
      <p class="text-primary-800 mb-4">
        Australia's BIIP suits investors seeking genuine residence with a clear permanent pathway, not just visa flexibility. The 188C is best for ultra-HNW individuals wanting minimal time commitment; 188A/B suit active business operators. Health insurance is mandatory during the 5-year provisional period—budget AUD 350-900/month for comprehensive international coverage. Work with registered migration agents and ensure you meet ongoing requirements to secure permanent residence.
      </p>
